In Banff and Jasper NPs, this species begins arriving in late April and, by early May, can be found daily. At its summer peak abundance, it is fairly common and seems to occur wherever buildings are to be found in montane and subalpine zones. The species can be found daily until late September, when sightings begin to drop off. The species appears to have been absent from the parks from about 1920 to about 1960 (J. Rogers, Naturalist, pers. comm. March 2009). 

Observed at 4 separate locations in West Banff in August 2010.  All observations were near park buildings (Saddleback staff residences, LL waste water treatment plant, Waterfowl campground staff residence, and Protection Mountain campground staff residence).  2010 observation data provided by S. Wrajez, Wildlife Technician, KYLL, to M. Tremblay, WNSC Calgary, 2010.09.13.

Banff National Park records for Bobolink include a male near the Banff townsite in May 1972, 2 pairs on May 27, 1972 in the lower Cascade River valley, 3 males on May 28, 1978 at Vermilion Lakes, and 2 males on June 4, 1977 at Banff townsite.  This specie sis described as a rare visitor in spring (Holroyd and Van Tighem, 1983). 

There are only about ten records of this species for Banff and Jasper NPs.  All were obtained between 1970 and 1994.  And all occur within the relatively small window of 23 May to 4 June indicating that the birds seen were spring migrants (Jason Rogers, pers. comm. March 2009). 

Species detected during 2006 Terrestrial Bird Surveys.

“In Canada, the breeding range of the Bobolink includes the Cariboo, and the Thompson-Nicola, Creston and Okanagan valleys of British Columbia, central and southern Alberta (from Beaverhill Lake to the border regions), where it appears to be sporadic (absent from the foothills of the Rockies), central and southern Saskatchewan, southern Manitoba central and southern Ontario, southern Québec, throughout New Brunswick, Prince Edward Island and Nova Scotia and southwestern and southeastern Newfoundland. Fall migration begins in mid-to-late July, with adults and immatures forming loose flocks close to the breeding grounds before heading for coastal habitats on the east coast, between New Jersey and Florida” (COSEWIC, 2010).

Bobolink is ranked MANA in Banff National Park because it is a long distance aerial migrant that rarely uses the park

References: 
COSEWIC. 2010. COSEWIC assessment and status report on the Bobolink Dolichonyx oryzivorus in Canada. Committee on the Status of Endangered Wildlife in Canada. Ottawa. vi + 43 pp.

Rogers, Jason.  Bird naturalist working on updating the bird checklist for Banff and Jasper National Parks. Pers. comm. March 2009.

There are 2 Banff records, one on May 10, 1977 at Vermilion Lakes and one in early June at Banff townsite.  Described as a very rare spring and summer visitor (Holroyd and Van Tighem 1983). 

Not recorded on Breeding Bird Surveys along Bow Pass route (017). 

In Banff and Jasper NPs, this species is a very rare spring and fall migrant. Spring sightings have been made from early May to early June. Fall sightings have been made in late August (J. Rogers, pers. comm. March 2009).

There is one record for Banff:  a male was seen on 25 April 1943 in the middle Bow River valley (Holroyd and Van Tighem 1983). 

This record was probably from Moose Meadows (J. Rogers, pers. comm.)

Common Nighthawk is believed to be an uncommon but regular breeder in the lower Bow & lower Red Deer valleys of Banff National Park (Banff National Park, ELC unpublished data) and is noted as a breeding bird in the Banff NP's 2011 Bird Checklist.

Considered a very rare migrant in Banff and Jasper Parks. Normally breeds in open grassland areas in southern Alberta;  not expected to breed in Banff NP.  There are 2 historic records from Banff, from 1945 (Banff Museum) and 1974 (North Saskatchewan River Crossing) (Holdroyd and Van Tighem 1983).  

No information to add to this (J. Rogers, pers. comm. March 2009).

There are two populations that occur in Banff NP: a migratory one (spring and fall only) and a "resident" one. Birds of the migratory population peak in abundance in spring from early March to early May and in fall from late September to early November. During these peaks, a competent birder is likely to spot 10+ eagles in a day if he/she knows where to look. However, this population appears to experiencing a significant and perhaps accelerating decline apparently resulting from increasing mortality on its winter range. The "resident" population appears to partially withdraw from the park in winter. At that time of year, even a competent birder is unlikely to find one in a day. At other times of the year, birds of the "resident" population are seen more often but still occur in a low density (J. Rogers, pers. comm.) 

Numerous obs from 1970-2000 in the random obs dbase.  Low low breeding densities throughout the park.  Decline in abundance since the 1940s. Species considered to be an "uncommon resident". (Holroyd and Van Tighem 1983).  

Numerous observations in the wildlife observations database from 1980-2000s.

1 observation in the middle Bow River valley in 1943 (Holroyd and Van Tighem 1983). 

This record is probably from Moose Meadows (J. Rogers, pers. comm.).

5 observations recorded, all in the lower Bow River valley and all in May and June between 1965 and early 1980s (Holroyd and Van Tighem 1983).  

"In Banff and Jasper NPs, this species is a rare spring migrant and summer visitor. Though it has never been found nesting in Banff NP, it did nest in Jasper NP in 1933/1934 and 1946. All sightings have been made between late April and late June. On average, sightings occur every few years with the most recent sighting being of two birds in Jasper NP on 11 May 2006" (J. Rogers, pers. comm. March 2009).

Although not common, is one of the most common flycatchers in Banff and Jasper Parks. Considered an uncommon summer resident (Holroyd and Van Tighem 1983). 

	Recorded on Breeding Bird Surveys on the Bow Pass route on 9 of the 15 years from 1986 and 2000 (Sauer et al 2008), though not since then; numerous historic records from the late 1970s (Banff NP data files; Tom Hurd, Wildlife Specialist, Banff NP, pers comm, March 2009).  Detected in 5 of 7 years in 2003-2009 along Smith Dorian Breeding Bird Survey Route # 196) in Kananaskis, south of Banff (outside the park).  

In Banff and Jasper NPs, this species appears to be in decline based on anecdotal observations from birders and its disappearance from the two Breeding Bird Survey routes along which it has historically been found. It's rare in mid and late May and becomes uncommon by the beginning of June. It remains uncommon through until the end of August, when it departs (J. Rogers, pers. comm. March 2009).

I would characterize rusty blackbird as a regular winter visitor in BNP. For example:  it has been reported 5 of the last 6 years on our Banff-Canmore Christmas Bird Count which I compile.  (Numbers ranged from 1 to 12.)  The most common location it is found is at the Cave and Basin marsh.  Some years the individual bird(s) stick around for a number of days if not weeks.  I have seen it on occasion in the early spring at Warner's Stables and wouldn't be surprised if it was a pretty regular visitor on migration at that time of year as well, but people may have more difficulty separating it from some other blackbirds that also are around in the spring. (Mike McIvor email to Jesse Whittington, 2006).

Described as a rare migrant. Records include 12 individuals on October 24, 1976 at Banff townsite and a winter record from 1976 also near Banff townsite (Holroyd and Van Tighem 1983).

In Banff and Jasper NPs, this species occurs as a rare spring migrant during the first three weeks of May. There are a handful of June and July records, but no evidence of nesting has ever been obtained for either park. The species occurs as a rare fall migrant from the beginning of September through to early November. There are three December records for the parks (J. Rogers, pers. comm.) 


2 records near Banff townsite in wildlife observations database, in 1985 and 1989.   

Holroyd and Van Tighem (1983) notes 13 records, most of which are during fall migration.  Species considered to be a "very rare visitor" (Holroyd and Van Tighem (1983).

There is only one record for BNP: one was seen on 8 June 1943 at Vermilion Lakes, i.e. during the spring migration period (Holroyd and Van Tighem 1983). 

One record in the LYKK_BAFU random observations database from 25 April 1980, near Banff townsite.
